com.epoch.chem
Class MolFunctions

java.lang.Object
  com.epoch.chem.MolFunctions
All Implemented Interfaces:
SearchConstants, StereoConstants, ChemConstants, FormatConstants
public final class MolFunctions
extends Object
implements ChemConstants, SearchConstants, StereoConstants

Contains molecule matching and normalization methods. Matching functions are:

  • matchPrecise() -- diagonal-only match; explicit and implicit H atoms are considered equivalent
  • matchPerfect() -- diagonal-only match; explicit H atoms in two structures must match exactly, too
  • matchNearPerfect() -- utility for matchPrecise() and matchPerfect()
  • matchExact() -- nondiagonal match; straight bond in author structure matches to any bond in response; explicit and implicit H are considered equivalent
  • matchPerfectLewis() -- like matchPerfect(), but unshared electrons must match too
  • matchSigmaNetwork() -- checks if the response contains the σ-bond network of the author's structure. All H atoms in response (unless it is a Lewis structure) and author's structure are made explicit, all multiple bonds are converted to single bonds, and two are compared ignoring charges and radicals (and implicit H atoms!) but considering explicit H atoms.
  • areResonanceStructures() -- if charge and σ-bond network are same but structures are different
  • areResonanceOrIdentical() -- if charge and σ-bond network are same
  • containsSubstruct() -- contains a substructure
  • matchConformers() -- determines whether two identical compounds are in the same conformation

matchPrecise

public static boolean matchPrecise(Molecule respMol,
                                   Molecule authMol)
                            throws MolFileException
Determines whether two molecules are identical: stereo bonds must match exactly, but explicit H atoms in one may be implicit in the other, and vice versa. Molecules are NOT modified, so they don't need to be cloned before coming here. Irrelevant which molecule is respMol and which is authMol, but retained for consistency.

Parameters:
respMol - a molecule
authMol - a molecule
Returns:
true if the molecules are exactly alike, including stereo bonds but not explicit/implicit H atoms
Throws:
MolFileException

Determines whether a response molecule (target in ChemAxon parlance) matches to an author's molecule (query). Any stereo bond in the author's molecule must be present in the response molecule, but a nonstereobond in the author's molecule matches to any stereo bond (or none) in the response molecule.

authMol - an author's molecule

matchExact

public static boolean matchExact(Molecule respMol,
                                 Molecule authMol,
                                 int matchFlags)
                          throws MolFileException
Determines whether a response molecule (target in ChemAxon parlance) (or maybe its enantiomer) matches to an author's molecule (query). If stereochemistry is not ignored, any stereo bond in the author's molecule must be present in the response molecule, but a nonstereobond in the author's molecule matches to any stereo bond (or none) in the response molecule. (Value of setImplicitHMatching() is set to IMPLICIT_H_MATCHING_ENABLED by default. DISABLED would mean that explicit H atoms in the author's substructure would have to be explicit in the response.)

Parameters:
respMol - a response molecule
authMol - an author's molecule
matchFlags - flags for treating stereochemistry, H matching, electrons matching, isotope matching
Returns:
true if the response molecule matches the author's molecule
Throws:
MolFileException

containsSubstruct

public static boolean containsSubstruct(Molecule respMol,
                                        Molecule substruct)
                                 throws MolFileException
Determines whether a response molecule (target in ChemAxon parlance) contains an author's substructure (query). Explicit H atoms in the author's substructure must be present (implicit or explicit) in the response. (Value of setImplicitHMatching() is set to IMPLICIT_H_MATCHING_ENABLED by default. DISABLED would mean that explicit H atoms in the author's substructure would have to be explicit in the response.) Charges, isotopes, and radicals in the author's structure must be present in the response, and vice versa.

Parameters:
respMol - the response molecule
substruct - the author's substructure as a molecule
Returns:
true if the response contains the substructure
Throws:
MolFileException

                                 throws MolFileException

Explicit H atoms in the author's substructure must be present (implicit or explicit) in the response. (Value of setImplicitHMatching() is set to IMPLICIT_H_MATCHING_ENABLED by default. DISABLED would mean that explicit H atoms in the author's substructure would have to be explicit in the response.)

Parameters:

substruct - the author's substructure as a molecule

normalize

public static String normalize(String molStruct)
                        throws MolFileException
Convert the String representation of this molecule into a "normalized" String representation to implement some chemical equivalencies.
  1. Aromatize.
  2. Ungroup shortcut groups.
  3. Remove spin state information from radicals.
  4. Convert every single bond of the form (S|Se|N|P|As)m+–(O|S|Se|N|C)n– into (S|Se|N|P|As)(m – 1)+=(O|S|Se|N|C)(n – 1)–, and treat similar double bonds similarly.
  5. For every stereo bond, if it is from a nonstereocenter to a stereocenter or to a double-bond atom, flip it. This will make sure that the student's response with opposite convention will be treated as correct.

Parameters:
molStruct - String representation of a molecule
Returns:
String representation of the normalized molecule
Throws:
MolFileException

normalize

public static Molecule normalize(Molecule origMol)
Convert a copy of this molecule into a "normalized" form to implement some chemical equivalencies.
  1. Aromatize.
  2. Ungroup shortcut groups.
  3. Remove spin state information from radicals.
  4. Convert every single bond of the form (S|Se|N|P|As)m+–(O|S|Se|N|C)n– into (S|Se|N|P|As)(m – 1)+=(O|S|Se|N|C)(n – 1)–, and treat similar double bonds similarly.
  5. For every stereo bond, if it is from a nonstereocenter to a stereocenter or to a double-bond atom, flip it. This will make sure that the student's response with opposite convention will be treated as correct.

Parameters:
origMol - a molecule
Returns:
normalized copy of the original molecule
